1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:03,600
After six failed SAS ideas, my seventh made millions.

2
00:00:03,600 --> 00:00:04,799
This is Jacob.

3
00:00:04,799 --> 00:00:08,160
He built a million-dollar SAS 100% with no code.

4
00:00:08,160 --> 00:00:10,480
So, you don't need to know how to actually code.

5
00:00:10,480 --> 00:00:12,080
You don't need to know code syntax.

6
00:00:12,080 --> 00:00:16,560
The tool he built it with and grew it from 0 to $1 million ARR.

7
00:00:16,560 --> 00:00:17,760
It's not lovable.

8
00:00:17,760 --> 00:00:18,960
It's not cursor.

9
00:00:18,960 --> 00:00:26,000
It's that's the best part of it is anyone can get started and understand the basic frameworks even of programming.

10
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:30,800
Jacob is proof that you don't need any coding experience to build a profitable SAS.

11
00:00:30,800 --> 00:00:34,480
And not knowing how to code might actually be a huge advantage.

12
00:00:34,480 --> 00:00:42,879
In this video, Jacob and Alex come on to the channel to break down exactly how they bootstrapped their SAS to $1 million in just 10 months.

13
00:00:42,879 --> 00:00:49,840
Plus, we'll talk about the secret to building MVPs with no code, the marketing strategy that exploded the business,

14
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:53,039
and how you can get started building apps without code.

15
00:00:53,039 --> 00:00:58,879
Today I'm Pat Walls and this is Starter Story.

16
00:00:58,879 --> 00:01:01,680
All right, welcome Jacob to Starter Story.

17
00:01:01,680 --> 00:01:05,040
Tell me a little about the business that you built and what's your story.

18
00:01:05,040 --> 00:01:08,159
My name is Jacob and I built a million-dollar business with no code.

19
00:01:08,159 --> 00:01:11,280
I'm a self-taught developer and the co-founder of Faceless Video.

20
00:01:11,280 --> 00:01:18,000
It's 100% bootstrapped and I built it from scratch with Bubble and it's now doing over a million dollars a year in ARR.

21
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:19,200
Wow, that's amazing.

22
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:24,560
Uh, can you give me a further breakdown of how Faceless works, what it does, and some of the numbers behind the business?

23
00:01:24,560 --> 00:01:30,320
It's a SAS that automates Faceless social media channels and the user only needs to provide their channel topic.

24
00:01:30,320 --> 00:01:36,880
And our platform writes the video content, creates the video, and posts that video on the user's behalf every single day,

25
00:01:36,880 --> 00:01:38,240
entirely on autopilot.

26
00:01:38,240 --> 00:01:41,600
We're generating thousands of videos every single day for users.

27
00:01:41,600 --> 00:01:45,920
Some of which had well over a million views, plenty of which have had hundreds of thousands of views.

28
00:01:45,920 --> 00:01:48,479
Total number of users signed up, over 1.1 million.

29
00:01:48,479 --> 00:01:51,680
and they're all hopping on current and relevant trends right now.

30
00:01:51,680 --> 00:01:53,759
That's an amazing business that you built.

31
00:01:53,759 --> 00:01:56,000
But I want to go back a little bit.

32
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,079
Uh what's your background and how do you get to the point of building a SAS?

33
00:02:00,079 --> 00:02:02,079
My background started as an artist.

34
00:02:02,079 --> 00:02:08,879
I uh started as a songwriter, producer, and I was releasing music on Spotify, diving full force into that world.

35
00:02:08,879 --> 00:02:14,000
So when I graduated college, I decided to live at home with my mom and go full force into being a songwriter,

36
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:15,040
artist, producer.

37
00:02:15,040 --> 00:02:22,640
I started hiring companies to do marketing for me, but I I was just repeatedly disappointed by all the different marketing services that I was getting.

38
00:02:22,640 --> 00:02:25,280
So, I just figured, okay, I got to go do this myself.

39
00:02:25,280 --> 00:02:34,160
So, I took courses online about how to market my music and with very little budget took my music to close to a million streams and thousands of genuine fans.

40
00:02:34,160 --> 00:02:38,959
That naturally progressed into helping my friends out in the music business and helping them promote their music,

41
00:02:38,959 --> 00:02:40,879
which turned into my first business, Domino.

42
00:02:40,879 --> 00:02:42,239
It's a music marketing agency.

43
00:02:42,239 --> 00:02:49,360
And while I love that experience, what I realized about doing a service-based business is that my income was directly correlated with my time.

44
00:02:49,360 --> 00:02:54,560
And I just wanted to scale beyond my agency and help more people without sacrificing more of my time.

45
00:02:54,560 --> 00:02:57,200
And that made me start looking into SAS.

46
00:02:57,200 --> 00:03:02,159
So, you caught the bug and then you came upon an idea that kind of changed everything.

47
00:03:02,159 --> 00:03:08,879
Let's talk about that idea and I actually had you bring your co-founder, Alex, on who was a part of coming up with that idea.

48
00:03:08,879 --> 00:03:10,640
So, Alex is joining us right now.

49
00:03:10,640 --> 00:03:12,080
I'd love to hear from you.

50
00:03:12,080 --> 00:03:15,280
Uh, how did you come up with the idea for Faceless Video?

51
00:03:15,280 --> 00:03:16,879
Yeah, so thanks for having me.

52
00:03:16,879 --> 00:03:21,040
I was getting a lot of Faceless videos on my Tik Tok algorithm.

53
00:03:21,040 --> 00:03:27,519
I had seen a lot of these videos go extremely viral, and my goal originally was just to go viral.

54
00:03:27,519 --> 00:03:29,840
And I thought to myself, I can edit these videos.

55
00:03:29,840 --> 00:03:30,959
You know, they look simple enough.

56
00:03:30,959 --> 00:03:32,000
They're going viral.

57
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:33,280
Why not do it myself?

58
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:36,480
But then I realized that consistency was a huge problem.

59
00:03:36,480 --> 00:03:43,040
and coming up with new ideas, editing every day became something that was actually pretty difficult to stick to.

60
00:03:43,040 --> 00:03:48,080
So, I had an idea because I realized with, you know, the advancements in tech that were going on,

61
00:03:48,080 --> 00:03:51,040
these videos were simple enough that this could be done automatically.

62
00:03:51,040 --> 00:03:58,720
And so, I reached out to Jacob and then Jacob had the idea to make this into a SAS product instead of an internal tool so we could make channels together.

63
00:03:58,720 --> 00:04:02,560
Looking back, I'm really glad that I let the algorithm guide me.

64
00:04:02,560 --> 00:04:09,519
And you know, we all are on Tik Tok and Instagram reels and we see these trends in videos and most of the time we scroll past.

65
00:04:09,519 --> 00:04:15,280
But if you take a second to actually analyze what's going on, there are plenty of good business ideas in there.

66
00:04:15,280 --> 00:04:18,160
So you have the idea, now it's time to get building.

67
00:04:18,160 --> 00:04:20,959
Tell me how how did you build Faceless Video?

68
00:04:20,959 --> 00:04:22,960
It started with Bubble and APIs.

69
00:04:22,960 --> 00:04:25,840
And Bubble was the infrastructure for bringing everything together.

70
00:04:25,840 --> 00:04:30,639
And like with anything else, it always starts with can this work from a technical perspective at least.

71
00:04:30,639 --> 00:04:36,479
You know, can I actually find a way to type in text and have this web app output a faceless video.

72
00:04:36,479 --> 00:04:38,720
So for the first month, that's really all this MVP was.

73
00:04:38,720 --> 00:04:44,320
And that eventually migrated into managing users, having a UIUX flow, a payment processing system,

74
00:04:44,320 --> 00:04:47,840
a pricing model, and turning it into a full-fledged web app.

75
00:04:47,840 --> 00:04:48,160
Okay.

76
00:04:48,160 --> 00:04:51,199
So tell me why Bubble is great for non-developers.

77
00:04:51,199 --> 00:04:55,280
In its simplest form, it translates programming into human language.

78
00:04:55,280 --> 00:04:57,759
So you don't need to know how to actually code.

79
00:04:57,759 --> 00:05:00,400
You don't need to know code syntax is plain English.

80
00:05:00,400 --> 00:05:06,639
And that's the best part of it is anyone can get started and understand the basic frameworks even of programming.

81
00:05:06,639 --> 00:05:13,280
Because now that I actually know how to code, I see that it is actually still very much programming just in a more visual human friendly way.

82
00:05:13,280 --> 00:05:18,639
And they also handle plenty of other important aspects of actually running a web app such as security,

83
00:05:18,639 --> 00:05:28,720
scalability, privacy rules, backend management, all these other things that I would not have even known where to begin if I was just coming at it completely fresh or custom.

84
00:05:28,720 --> 00:05:32,720
You know, I talked to a lot of people who will start their app on Bubble, but then, you know,

85
00:05:32,720 --> 00:05:36,639
once things get too complicated and they really want to scale, they have to move off it,

86
00:05:36,639 --> 00:05:38,000
which ends up being a huge thing.

87
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:42,320
But as I understand, you your app, which is making a million dollars a year right now,

88
00:05:42,320 --> 00:05:43,759
is still on Bubble.

89
00:05:43,759 --> 00:05:46,240
Why have you decided to stay on Bubble?

90
00:05:46,240 --> 00:05:47,840
If it ain't broke, don't fix it.

91
00:05:47,840 --> 00:05:49,120
It's kind of as simple as that.

92
00:05:49,120 --> 00:05:52,639
You know, we haven't run into any issues that would require a dramatic shift.

93
00:05:52,639 --> 00:06:00,400
I I ran into a scalability issue once, but Bubble support fixed it, and that was really good piece of mind for staying longterm with them.

94
00:06:00,400 --> 00:06:06,400
And realistically, all the bells and whistles that developers get through custom code is not necessary for building a successful business.

95
00:06:06,400 --> 00:06:10,880
All you need is a great idea, a functioning product, and a great go to market strategy,

96
00:06:10,880 --> 00:06:14,080
and you can validate really quickly and scale based on that.

97
00:06:14,080 --> 00:06:17,360
All right, let's pause for a quick moment to talk about AI.

98
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:21,360
Everyone's hyped up right now about using AI to build apps.

99
00:06:21,360 --> 00:06:26,800
But right now, I'm seeing that most people get stuck in what I call a death spiral of prompting.

100
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:30,800
They have lots of chats with the AI, but the code never actually works.

101
00:06:30,800 --> 00:06:33,840
And that's exactly why we're partnering with Bubble.

102
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:37,199
Bubble AI doesn't put your idea into a cookie cutter template.

103
00:06:37,199 --> 00:06:40,880
It actually blows it up into a full stack working app.

104
00:06:40,880 --> 00:06:46,479
All you have to do is describe your idea and Bubble AI will spin up the entire stack in minutes.

105
00:06:46,479 --> 00:06:52,240
A polished UI, a pre-wired database, and workflows that are ready to roll.

106
00:06:52,240 --> 00:06:55,120
I've been poking around with it to build some stuff for Starter Story.

107
00:06:55,120 --> 00:06:59,759
And watching it just build everything while I sit there and enjoy my drink is pretty amazing.

108
00:06:59,759 --> 00:07:05,120
So, if you've been sitting on an idea, head to the first link in the description, sign up for free,

109
00:07:05,120 --> 00:07:08,160
and tell Bubble AI exactly what you want to build.

110
00:07:08,160 --> 00:07:10,639
If you do that, drop your idea in the comments.

111
00:07:10,639 --> 00:07:12,960
I'll read through them and let you know which ones are my favorite.

112
00:07:12,960 --> 00:07:15,919
All right, let's dive back into Jacob and Alex story.

113
00:07:15,919 --> 00:07:24,639
On that note, um, what would be some of the opportunities that you see right now for ideas that people could build with Bubble or other no code tools?

114
00:07:24,639 --> 00:07:27,360
I think marketplaces are kind of the first thing that comes to mind actually.

115
00:07:27,360 --> 00:07:32,000
Just because it's the easiest way to manage a front end and a backend through no code.

116
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:35,759
It's a little bit more generic, but honestly, you can build anything if you get creative.

117
00:07:35,759 --> 00:07:38,880
But even if it's no code, that doesn't necessarily mean that it's easy.

118
00:07:38,880 --> 00:07:40,080
Uh you still have to get creative.

119
00:07:40,080 --> 00:07:44,560
You still need to be resourceful, but there's plenty of opportunities with no code.

120
00:07:44,560 --> 00:07:48,639
And it brings down the barrier to entry enough so that you can start.

121
00:07:48,639 --> 00:07:50,960
And starting is the biggest hurdle.

122
00:07:50,960 --> 00:07:52,160
Well, that's awesome.

123
00:07:52,160 --> 00:07:55,599
So, I want to switch gears to marketing distribution.

124
00:07:55,599 --> 00:08:00,720
How did you take this idea from zero to a million dollars a year?

125
00:08:00,720 --> 00:08:05,360
To have success as a B2C app, you need to have viral potential.

126
00:08:05,360 --> 00:08:08,879
Your CAC, customer acquisition costs, it's pretty low.

127
00:08:08,879 --> 00:08:15,840
And so, to spend a lot on ads or other methods of promotion is not really viable for a a B2C app.

128
00:08:15,840 --> 00:08:19,360
That's something I learned with Faces that my other products really didn't have.

129
00:08:19,360 --> 00:08:20,639
We didn't reinvent the wheel.

130
00:08:20,639 --> 00:08:26,000
We do all of the usual stuff, you know, we do SEO, we do ads, influencers, organic content,

131
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:30,080
but the key is really getting your messaging right and it's nothing fancy.

132
00:08:30,080 --> 00:08:31,440
It's just good execution.

133
00:08:31,440 --> 00:08:36,000
So, I come from a film making background and that's a lot about storytelling.

134
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:39,599
So, if you can crack storytelling, then you can really sell a product.

135
00:08:39,599 --> 00:08:44,880
What you want to do is kickstart telling that story with ads, influencer collaborations,

136
00:08:44,880 --> 00:08:45,600
and other things.

137
00:08:45,600 --> 00:08:46,800
That's what Jacob and I did.

138
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:56,959
Our first advertisement for Faceless Video was a Twitter thread that we spent I don't know like 200 bucks on and we got hundreds of thousands of views and kind of instantly went viral.

139
00:08:56,959 --> 00:08:59,279
Um, and that was very very helpful for us.

140
00:08:59,279 --> 00:09:09,360
And also our biggest growth came when influencers who saw our ads that we'd never even reached out to started promoting Faceless.video on their own because they genuinely believe that their audience

141
00:09:09,360 --> 00:09:10,480
would like the product.

142
00:09:10,480 --> 00:09:16,560
And Jacob also knows this, but word of mouth is consistently one of our top five attribution sources.

143
00:09:16,560 --> 00:09:19,920
So like on our customer attribution thing, people will just type in friend.

144
00:09:19,920 --> 00:09:22,080
So you know, people actually like the product.

145
00:09:22,080 --> 00:09:27,519
But if you have something that's truly original and solves a pain point, especially around an emerging trend,

146
00:09:27,519 --> 00:09:30,399
people will notice if you're first to market with something.

147
00:09:30,399 --> 00:09:38,240
So that's what we kind of centered our whole marketing strategy around is showing how are we different from what's out there?

148
00:09:38,240 --> 00:09:42,480
And then also this is how you can tap into this existing trend in a new way.

149
00:09:42,480 --> 00:09:47,519
So you can lay the foundation with traditional marketing like ads, influencers and all these things.

150
00:09:47,519 --> 00:09:53,760
But virality happens when the product kind of speaks for itself and you have the proper messaging and all of the incentives are lined up.

151
00:09:53,760 --> 00:09:59,360
I want to switch gears a little bit and talk about uh this business that you built and how it's impacted you.

152
00:09:59,360 --> 00:10:03,440
Uh you had a lot of failed businesses before, then you had this thing kind of take off.

153
00:10:03,440 --> 00:10:06,880
I'd love to hear more about that experience and how it changed things.

154
00:10:06,880 --> 00:10:08,640
SAS is incredible.

155
00:10:08,640 --> 00:10:10,640
I think that's kind of the first thing I I have to say.

156
00:10:10,640 --> 00:10:18,399
I went from a servicebased business into into SAS and it just allows you to make more money while getting your time back.

157
00:10:18,399 --> 00:10:19,519
And that that's huge.

158
00:10:19,519 --> 00:10:23,360
With a properly running system, your business will make money for you while you sleep.

159
00:10:23,360 --> 00:10:30,399
That doesn't mean it's hands off though while you're awake, of course, but I I was just amazed by how the system can really work when it connects.

160
00:10:30,399 --> 00:10:40,160
Something else that I realized a little bit maybe more on the personal side is it's important to make sure that what you're pursuing is for the love of doing it because when times get hard it it's easy to quit.

161
00:10:40,160 --> 00:10:45,680
It also gives us a competitive advantage because Jacob and I truly love doing this business and we're obsessed with it.

162
00:10:45,680 --> 00:10:46,880
We're always thinking about it.

163
00:10:46,880 --> 00:10:51,519
We're always texting each other about the business and if it's not truly something you love,

164
00:10:51,519 --> 00:10:54,399
someone who loves doing it, they'll always surpass you.

165
00:10:54,399 --> 00:10:55,839
You have this successful business.

166
00:10:55,839 --> 00:10:57,680
You get to sit down and work on it every day.

167
00:10:57,680 --> 00:10:58,640
You're passionate about it.

168
00:10:58,640 --> 00:11:01,519
What does an actual day in the life look like for you?

169
00:11:01,519 --> 00:11:02,640
You have a million- dollar business.

170
00:11:02,640 --> 00:11:03,600
What does that look like?

171
00:11:03,600 --> 00:11:06,000
Every day it kind of sits into two different buckets.

172
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:10,880
I'm either looking into ways to cut costs, make things more efficient, improve the product,

173
00:11:10,880 --> 00:11:14,560
or bring on completely new features, integrations, and partnerships.

174
00:11:14,560 --> 00:11:17,600
That's kind of what a day in the life looks like is just constant optimizations.

175
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:19,040
I'm still doing bug reports, too.

176
00:11:19,040 --> 00:11:21,680
So, there's of course the mundane side of things as well.

177
00:11:21,680 --> 00:11:23,360
For me, it's more of a balancing act.

178
00:11:23,360 --> 00:11:28,079
It's just finding new ways to grow while keeping our existing channels running smoothly.

179
00:11:28,079 --> 00:11:33,200
So, you know, creative strategy, working with our new team, as Jacob said, managing partnerships.

180
00:11:33,200 --> 00:11:37,680
So, it's just figuring out how to scale while also not breaking what's already working.

181
00:11:37,680 --> 00:11:38,560
Thanks for sharing that.

182
00:11:38,560 --> 00:11:43,760
Last question we ask all founders is if you can stand on Jacob and Alex's shoulders when you're just starting out before the success,

183
00:11:43,760 --> 00:11:44,640
what would you tell them?

184
00:11:44,640 --> 00:11:46,640
There's there's three things that come to mind for me.

185
00:11:46,640 --> 00:11:50,880
The the first is build from day zero optimizing for the best case scenario.

186
00:11:50,880 --> 00:11:54,160
If a 100,000 people signed up today, could your app handle it?

187
00:11:54,160 --> 00:11:58,800
Or would you have to rethink your pricing model and your technical debt when that starts to happen?

188
00:11:58,800 --> 00:12:01,200
The other thing is to not get too attached.

189
00:12:01,200 --> 00:12:06,079
If I didn't go through six ideas before Faceless, I probably still would have been trying to make that first idea work,

190
00:12:06,079 --> 00:12:08,240
and it just may not have worked at all.

191
00:12:08,240 --> 00:12:09,519
Maybe the idea wasn't good enough.

192
00:12:09,519 --> 00:12:11,040
Failing fast is a win-win.

193
00:12:11,040 --> 00:12:13,120
It there's no lose scenario with that.

194
00:12:13,120 --> 00:12:20,000
The third thing that comes to mind is to stay bootstrapped cuz staying bootstrapped forces you to build lean and and really focus on your value.

195
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:23,519
If your idea is valuable to others, then you can scale healthfully.

196
00:12:23,519 --> 00:12:26,800
And if it's not, then you can move on and adapt quickly.

197
00:12:26,800 --> 00:12:27,680
You have options.

198
00:12:27,680 --> 00:12:29,600
So, I've been doing this since I've been young.

199
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:30,880
I've always built things.

200
00:12:30,880 --> 00:12:32,800
But don't watch generic tutorials.

201
00:12:32,800 --> 00:12:38,720
Just pick a project that you're genuinely excited about and then learn everything you need to make that project real.

202
00:12:38,720 --> 00:12:42,720
You'll learn, you know, 10 times faster by building something you actually care about.

203
00:12:42,720 --> 00:12:47,279
And also, you can leverage your existing skills that you think might not apply to building a business.

204
00:12:47,279 --> 00:12:52,000
I don't think our marketing would have been as strong if I didn't have a storytelling background.

205
00:12:52,000 --> 00:13:00,720
And I don't think that, you know, a lot of what Jacob did, you know, come to fruition if he didn't have his background in the music industry and the advertising industry.

206
00:13:00,720 --> 00:13:01,920
Thank you, Alex.

207
00:13:01,920 --> 00:13:03,519
Thank you, Jacob, for coming on.

208
00:13:03,519 --> 00:13:05,279
The business you guys built is amazing.

209
00:13:05,279 --> 00:13:06,880
I'm sure it's going to keep growing.

210
00:13:06,880 --> 00:13:09,440
The fact you built it on Bubble is also amazing.

211
00:13:09,440 --> 00:13:11,680
I haven't heard of that before, but I think that's awesome.

212
00:13:11,680 --> 00:13:14,560
Thanks for coming on Starter Story and have a great day.

213
00:13:14,560 --> 00:13:15,920
Thank you so much for having us.

214
00:13:15,920 --> 00:13:16,560
Thank you.

215
00:13:16,560 --> 00:13:23,519
I love Jacob's story because he went from having basically no coding experience to building a million-dollar app.

